    "content": {
      "s0": {
        "mindset": {
          "heading": "Why Variables Matter",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "content": "Every program needs to **remember information**. Variables are how Python remembers things for you."
            }
          ]
        },
        "recap": {
          "heading": "From Printing to Remembering",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "content": "So far, you printed text directly. But what if you want to reuse information later?"
            }
          ]
        },
        "core": {
          "heading": "What Is a Variable?",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "content": "**A variable is a name that stores a value.** Think of it as a labeled box where you keep information."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "content": "Real-world examples:\n- Your name\n- Your age\n- A game score\n- Whether a light is on or off\n- The price of an item"
            },
            {
              "type": "code",
              "language": "python",
              "content": "age = 12\nprint(age)",
              "copyable": true
            }
          ]
        },
        "guidedPractice": {
          "heading": "Seeing Variables in Action",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "multipleChoice",
              "question": "What does a variable do?",
              "options": [
                "Prints text only",
                "Stores information",
                "Deletes data",
                "Runs Python"
              ],
              "correctIndex": 1,
              "feedback": {
                "correct": "Correct! Variables store information.",
                "incorrect": "Variables are used to remember values."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        "challenge": {
          "heading": "Think About Your Own Variables",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "shortAnswer",
              "prompt": "Name one thing in your life that could be stored in a variable.",
              "validation": { "type": "freeform" }
            }
          ]
        },
        "reflection": {
          "heading": "Reflection",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "checklist",
              "items": [
                "I know what a variable is",
                "I know why variables are useful",
                "I am ready to learn types"
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        "transition": {
          "heading": "Next Step",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "content": "Next, you’ll learn that not all values are the same — they have **types**."
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      "s1": {
        "mindset": {
          "heading": "Learning the Language",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "content": "Now we name and recognize the most common data types in Python."
            }
          ]
        },
        "recap": {
          "heading": "Variables Store Values",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "content": "A variable stores a value — but values come in different forms."
            }
          ]
        },
        "core": {
          "heading": "Basic Data Types",
          "components": [
            { "type": "text", "content": "**int** – whole numbers (e.g. 5)" },
            { "type": "text", "content": "**float** – decimal numbers (e.g. 3.14)" },
            { "type": "text", "content": "**str** – text (e.g. \"Hello\")" },
            { "type": "text", "content": "**bool** – true or false values (True / False)" }
          ]
        },
        "guidedPractice": {
          "heading": "Match the Type",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "matching",
              "leftColumn": ["5", "3.5", "\"Hi\"", "True"],
              "rightColumn": [
                { "definition": "Integer", "matchesWith": "5" },
                { "definition": "Float", "matchesWith": "3.5" },
                { "definition": "String", "matchesWith": "\"Hi\"" },
                { "definition": "Boolean", "matchesWith": "True" }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        "challenge": {
          "heading": "Type Recognition",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "shortAnswer",
              "prompt": "What data type is the value 10.0?",
              "validation": { "type": "contains", "acceptedAnswers": ["float"] }
            }
          ]
        },
        "reflection": {
          "heading": "Check Yourself",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "checklist",
              "items": [
                "I can name the four basic data types",
                "I can recognize examples of each"
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        "transition": {
          "heading": "Understanding Comes Next",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "content": "Next, you’ll learn how Python knows which type a variable has."
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      "s2": {
        "mindset": {
          "heading": "Understanding What Happens",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "content": "Now we open the black box and see how Python handles variables and types."
            }
          ]
        },
        "recap": {
          "heading": "Types Review",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "content": "Variables store values, and values have types."
            }
          ]
        },
        "core": {
          "heading": "How Python Handles Types",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "content": "Python automatically decides the type based on the value you assign."
            },
            {
              "type": "code",
              "language": "python",
              "content": "x = 5\ny = \"Hello\"\nprint(type(x))\nprint(type(y))",
              "copyable": true
            }
          ]
        },
        "guidedPractice": {
          "heading": "Predict the Type",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "multipleChoice",
              "question": "What is the type of x = 7?",
              "options": ["str", "int", "float", "bool"],
              "correctIndex": 1,
              "feedback": {
                "correct": "Correct! Whole numbers are integers.",
                "incorrect": "Remember: whole numbers without decimals are ints."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        "challenge": {
          "heading": "Explain It",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "shortAnswer",
              "prompt": "Why is \"5\" a string but 5 is an integer?",
              "validation": { "type": "freeform" }
            }
          ]
        },
        "reflection": {
          "heading": "Reflection",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "checklist",
              "items": [
                "I understand how Python assigns types",
                "I can explain the difference between values"
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        "transition": {
          "heading": "Time to Do It Yourself",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "content": "Next, you’ll start creating and using variables on your own."
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      "s3": {
        "mindset": {
          "heading": "Hands On",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "content": "Now you’ll actively create and use variables."
            }
          ]
        },
        "recap": {
          "heading": "Before You Start",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "content": "You know variables, types, and how Python assigns them."
            }
          ]
        },
        "core": {
          "heading": "Using Variables",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "code",
              "language": "python",
              "content": "name = \"Alex\"\nage = 13\nis_student = True\nprint(name)\nprint(age)\nprint(is_student)",
              "copyable": true
            }
          ]
        },
        "guidedPractice": {
          "heading": "Try It",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "shortAnswer",
              "prompt": "Create a variable called score with a value of 100. What type is it?",
              "validation": { "type": "contains", "acceptedAnswers": ["int"] }
            }
          ]
        },
        "challenge": {
          "heading": "Mini Task",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "shortAnswer",
              "prompt": "Write three variables about yourself and their types.",
              "validation": { "type": "freeform" }
            }
          ]
        },
        "reflection": {
          "heading": "Confidence Check",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "checklist",
              "items": [
                "I can create variables",
                "I can print variable values",
                "I understand their types"
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        "transition": {
          "heading": "Next Challenge",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "content": "Next, you’ll learn what happens when things go wrong."
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      "s4": {
        "mindset": {
          "heading": "Think Like a Detective",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "content": "Errors help you understand how Python thinks."
            }
          ]
        },
        "recap": {
          "heading": "What Works",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "content": "Correct variables have names and valid values."
            }
          ]
        },
        "core": {
          "heading": "Common Errors",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "content": "**NameError**: Using a variable before defining it."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "content": "**TypeError**: Using incompatible types together."
            }
          ]
        },
        "guidedPractice": {
          "heading": "Spot the Error",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "multipleChoice",
              "question": "What error occurs if you print(x) before defining x?",
              "options": ["TypeError", "NameError", "SyntaxError", "ValueError"],
              "correctIndex": 1,
              "feedback": {
                "correct": "Correct! x does not exist yet.",
                "incorrect": "The variable name is unknown."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        "challenge": {
          "heading": "Explain an Error",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "shortAnswer",
              "prompt": "Why does adding a string and a number cause an error?",
              "validation": { "type": "freeform" }
            }
          ]
        },
        "reflection": {
          "heading": "Troubleshooting Mindset",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "checklist",
              "items": [
                "I can recognize NameError",
                "I understand type mismatches"
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        "transition": {
          "heading": "Judging Code Quality",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "content": "Next, you’ll learn to decide which variable choices are better."
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      "s5": {
        "mindset": {
          "heading": "Choosing Better Code",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "content": "Good code is not just correct — it is clear."
            }
          ]
        },
        "recap": {
          "heading": "What You Know",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "content": "You can create and analyze variables."
            }
          ]
        },
        "core": {
          "heading": "Evaluating Variable Use",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "content": "Good variable names are clear, meaningful, and readable."
            }
          ]
        },
        "guidedPractice": {
          "heading": "Choose the Best Name",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "multipleChoice",
              "question": "Which variable name is best for a student’s age?",
              "options": ["x", "a1", "studentAge", "value"],
              "correctIndex": 2,
              "feedback": {
                "correct": "Correct! Clear and descriptive.",
                "incorrect": "Good names describe the data."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        "challenge": {
          "heading": "Justify Your Choice",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "shortAnswer",
              "prompt": "Why is clear naming important in programming?",
              "validation": { "type": "freeform" }
            }
          ]
        },
        "reflection": {
          "heading": "Quality Check",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "checklist",
              "items": [
                "I choose meaningful variable names",
                "I can explain my choices"
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        "transition": {
          "heading": "Time to Create",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "content": "Now you’ll create something using variables."
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      "s6": {
        "mindset": {
          "heading": "You Are the Creator",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "content": "You now combine everything into your own mini program."
            }
          ]
        },
        "recap": {
          "heading": "Full Journey",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "content": "You learned variables, types, errors, and quality."
            }
          ]
        },
        "core": {
          "heading": "Project Ideas",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "content": "Create a program that stores and prints:\n- Your name\n- Your age\n- Whether you like Python"
            }
          ]
        },
        "guidedPractice": {
          "heading": "Plan",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "shortAnswer",
              "prompt": "What variables will your program need?",
              "validation": { "type": "freeform" }
            }
          ]
        },
        "challenge": {
          "heading": "Build It",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "shortAnswer",
              "prompt": "Write your program and explain what each variable stores.",
              "validation": { "type": "freeform" }
            }
          ]
        },
        "reflection": {
          "heading": "Mastery Check",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "checklist",
              "items": [
                "I can create variables confidently",
                "I understand data types",
                "I can explain my code"
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        "transition": {
          "heading": "Congratulations",
          "components": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "content": "You are ready to learn **input, math operations, and conditions** next!"
            }
          ]
        }
      }
    },
    "ui": {
      "defaultExpandedStage": "s0"
